[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] In computer programming, especially in functional programming and type theory, an **algebraic data type** (**ADT**) is a composite data type, i.e. a type formed by combining other types.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] An algebraic data type is defined by two key constructions: a *sum* and a *product*.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] These are sometimes referred to as "OR" and "AND" types.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] A **sum type** is a choice between possibilities.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The value of a sum type can match one of several defined *variants*.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] For example, a type representing the state of a traffic light could be either `Red`, `Amber`, or `Green`.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] A shape type could be either a `Circle` (which stores a radius) *or* a `Square` (which stores a width).
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] In formal terms, these variants are known as tagged unions or disjoint unions.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Each variant has a name, called a **constructor**, which can also carry data.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Enumerated types are a simple form of sum type where the constructors carry no data.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] A **product type** combines types together.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] A value of a product type will contain a value for each of its component types.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] For example, a `Point` type might be defined to contain an `x` coordinate (an integer) *and* a `y` coordinate (also an integer).
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Formal examples of product types include tuples and records.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The set of all possible values of a product type is the Cartesian product of the sets of its component types.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Values of algebraic data types are typically handled using pattern matching.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] This feature allows a programmer to check which constructor a value was made with and extract the data it contains in a convenient and type-safe way.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types were introduced in Hope, a small functional programming language developed in the 1970s at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] One of the most common examples of an algebraic data type is the singly linked list.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] A list type is a sum type with two variants, `Nil` for an empty list and `Cons *x* *xs*` for the combination of a new element *x* with a list *xs* to create a new list.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] `Cons` is an abbreviation of *cons*truct.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Many languages have special syntax for lists defined in this way.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] For example, Haskell and ML use `[]` for `Nil`, `:` or `::` for `Cons`, respectively, and square brackets for entire lists.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Here, `Empty` represents an empty tree, `Leaf` represents a leaf node, and `Node` organizes the data into branches.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] In most languages that support algebraic data types, it is possible to define parametric types.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Examples are given later in this article.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Somewhat similar to a function, a data constructor is applied to arguments of an appropriate type, yielding an instance of the data type to which the type constructor belongs.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] For example, the data constructor `Leaf` is logically a function `Int -> Tree`, meaning that giving an integer as an argument to `Leaf` produces a value of the type `Tree`.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] As `Node` takes two arguments of the type `Tree` itself, the datatype is recursive.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Operations on algebraic data types can be defined by using pattern matching to retrieve the arguments.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Thus, a `Tree` given to `depth` can be constructed using any of `Empty`, `Leaf`, or `Node` and must be matched for any of them respectively to deal with all cases.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] In case of `Node`, the pattern extracts the subtrees `l` and `r` for further processing.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types are highly suited to implementing abstract syntax.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] An element of such a data type would have a form such as `Mult (Add (Number 4) (Minus (Number 0) (Number 1))) (Number 2)`.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Writing an evaluation function for this language is a simple exercise; however, more complex transformations also become feasible.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] For example, an optimization pass in a compiler might be written as a function taking an abstract expression as input and returning an optimized form.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types are used to represent values that can be one of several *types of things*.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Each type of thing is associated with an identifier called a *constructor*, which can be considered a tag for that kind of data.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Each constructor can carry with it a different type of data.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] For example, considering the binary `Tree` example shown above, a constructor could carry no data (e.g., `Empty`), or one piece of data (e.g., `Leaf` has one Int value), or multiple pieces of data (e.g., `Node` has one `Int` value and two `Tree` values).
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] To do something with a value of this `Tree` algebraic data type, it is *deconstructed* using a process called pattern matching.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] This involves matching the data with a series of *patterns*.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The example function `depth` above pattern-matches its argument with three patterns.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] When the function is called, it finds the first pattern that matches its argument, performs any variable bindings that are found in the pattern, and evaluates the expression corresponding to the pattern.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Each pattern above has a form that resembles the structure of some possible value of this datatype.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The first pattern simply matches values of the constructor `Empty`.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The second pattern matches values of the constructor `Leaf`.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Patterns are recursive, so then the data that is associated with that constructor is matched with the pattern "n".
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] In this case, a lowercase identifier represents a pattern that matches any value, which then is bound to a variable of that name — in this case, a variable "`n`" is bound to the integer value stored in the data type — to be used in the expression to evaluate.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Recursive patterns several layers deep are used for example in balancing red–black trees, which involve cases that require looking at colors several layers deep.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The advantages of algebraic data types can be highlighted by comparison of the above pseudocode with a pattern matching equivalent.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] In the pseudocode example above, programmer diligence is required to not access field2 when the constructor is a `Leaf`.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The type system would have difficulties assigning a static type in a safe way for traditional record data structures.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] However, in pattern matching such problems are not faced.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The type of each extracted value is based on the types declared by the relevant constructor.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The number of values that can be extracted is known based on the constructor.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Secondly, in pattern matching, the compiler performs exhaustiveness checking to ensure all cases are handled.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] If one of the cases of the *depth* function above were missing, the compiler would issue a warning.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Exhaustiveness checking may seem easy for simple patterns, but with many complex recursive patterns, the task soon becomes difficult for the average human (or compiler, if it must check arbitrary nested if-else constructs).
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Similarly, there may be patterns which never match (i.e., are already covered by prior patterns).
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The compiler can also check and issue warnings for these, as they may indicate an error in reasoning.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data type pattern matching should not be confused with regular expression string pattern matching.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The purpose of both is similar (to extract parts from a piece of data matching certain constraints) however, the implementation is very different.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Pattern matching on algebraic data types matches on the structural properties of an object rather than on the character sequence of strings.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] A general algebraic data type is a possibly recursive sum type of product types.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Each constructor tags a product type to separate it from others, or if there is only one constructor, the data type is a product type.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] Further, the parameter types of a constructor are the factors of the product type.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] A parameterless constructor corresponds to the empty product.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] If a datatype is recursive, the entire sum of products is wrapped in a recursive type, and each constructor also rolls the datatype into the recursive type.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] is represented in type theory as $\lambda \alpha .\mu \beta .1+\alpha \times \beta$ with constructors $\mathrm {nil} _{\alpha }=\mathrm {roll} \ (\mathrm {inl} \ \langle \rangle )$ and $\mathrm {cons} _{\alpha }\ x\ l=\mathrm {roll} \ (\mathrm {inr} \ \langle x,l\rangle )$ .
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The Haskell List datatype can also be represented in type theory in a slightly different form, thus: $\mu \phi .\lambda \alpha .1+\alpha \times \phi \ \alpha$ .
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] (Note how the $\mu$ and $\lambda$ constructs are reversed relative to the original.) The original formation specified a type function whose body was a recursive type.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] The revised version specifies a recursive function on types.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] (The type variable $\phi$ is used to suggest a function rather than a *base type* like $\beta$ , since $\phi$ is like a Greek *f*.) The function must also now be applied $\phi$ to its argument type $\alpha$ in the body of the type.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] For the purposes of the List example, these two formulations are not significantly different; but the second form allows expressing so-called nested data types, i.e., those where the recursive type differs parametrically from the original.
[src:reasonml/algebraic-data-type] In set theory the equivalent of a sum type is a disjoint union, a set whose elements are pairs consisting of a tag (equivalent to a constructor) and an object of a type corresponding to the tag (equivalent to the constructor arguments).
[src:reasonml/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:reasonml/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:reasonml/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:reasonml/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:reasonml/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:reasonml/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:reasonml/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:reasonml/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:reasonml/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:reasonml/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:reasonml/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:reasonml/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:reasonml/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:reasonml/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:reasonml/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:reasonml/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:reasonml/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:reasonml/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:reasonml/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:reasonml/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:reasonml/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:reasonml/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:reasonml/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:reasonml/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:reasonml/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:reasonml/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:reasonml/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:reasonml/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:reasonml/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:reasonml/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:reasonml/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:reasonml/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:reasonml/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:reasonml/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:reasonml/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:reasonml/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:reasonml/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:reasonml/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:reasonml/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:reasonml/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:reasonml/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:reasonml/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:reasonml/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:reasonml/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:reasonml/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:reasonml/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:reasonml/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:reasonml/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:reasonml/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:reasonml/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
