[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:reasonml/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:reasonml/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:reasonml/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:reasonml/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:reasonml/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:reasonml/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:reasonml/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:reasonml/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:reasonml/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:reasonml/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:reasonml/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:reasonml/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:reasonml/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:reasonml/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:reasonml/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:reasonml/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:reasonml/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:reasonml/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:reasonml/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:reasonml/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:reasonml/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:reasonml/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:reasonml/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:reasonml/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:reasonml/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:reasonml/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:reasonml/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:reasonml/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:reasonml/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:reasonml/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM) together with a composable build system for OCaml (Dune).
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml was developed first in the context of automated theorem proving, and is used in static analysis and formal methods software.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Beyond these areas, it has found use in systems programming, web development, and specific financial utilities, among other application domains.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] The acronym *CAML* originally stood for *Categorical Abstract Machine Language*, but OCaml omits this abstract machine.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml is a free and open-source software project managed and principally maintained by the French Institute for Research in Computer Science and Automation (Inria).
[src:reasonml/ocaml] In the early 2000s, elements from OCaml were adopted by many languages, notably F# and Scala.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] ML-derived languages are best known for their static type systems and type-inferring compilers.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml unifies functional, imperative, and object-oriented programming under an ML-like type system.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Thus, programmers need not be highly familiar with the pure functional language paradigm to use OCaml.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] By requiring the programmer to work within the constraints of its static type system, OCaml eliminates many of the type-related runtime problems associated with dynamically typed languages.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Also, OCaml's type-inferring compiler greatly reduces the need for the manual type annotations that are required in most statically typed languages.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] For example, the data types of variables and the signatures of functions usually need not be declared explicitly, as they do in languages like Java and C#, because they can be inferred from the operators and other functions that are applied to the variables and other values in the code.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Effective use of OCaml's type system can require some sophistication on the part of a programmer, but this discipline is rewarded with reliable, high-performance software.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml is perhaps most distinguished from other languages with origins in academia by its emphasis on performance.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] These are rare enough that avoiding them is quite possible in practice.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Aside from type-checking overhead, functional programming languages are, in general, challenging to compile to efficient machine language code, due to issues such as the funarg problem.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Xavier Leroy has stated that "OCaml delivers at least 50% of the performance of a decent C compiler", although a direct comparison is impossible.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Some functions in the OCaml standard library are implemented with faster algorithms than equivalent functions in the standard libraries of other languages.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Between the 1970s and 1980s, Robin Milner, a British computer scientist and Turing Award winner, worked at the University of Edinburgh's Laboratory for Foundations of Computer Science.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Milner and others were working on theorem provers, which were historically developed in languages such as Lisp.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Milner repeatedly ran into the issue that the theorem provers would attempt to claim a proof was valid by putting non-proofs together.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] As a result, he went on to develop the meta language for his Logic for Computable Functions, a language that would only allow the writer to construct valid proofs with its polymorphic type system.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] ML was turned into a compiler to simplify using LCF on different machines, and, by the 1980s, was turned into a complete system of its own.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] ML would eventually serve as a basis for the creation of OCaml.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] In the early 1980s, there were some developments that prompted INRIA's Formel team to become interested in the ML language.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Luca Cardelli, a research professor at University of Oxford, used his *functional abstract machine* to develop a faster implementation of ML, and Robin Milner proposed a new definition of ML to avoid divergence between various implementations.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Simultaneously, Pierre-Louis Curien, a senior researcher at Paris Diderot University, developed a calculus of categorical combinators and linked it to lambda calculus, which led to the definition of the *categorical abstract machine* (CAM).
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Guy Cousineau, a researcher at Paris Diderot University, recognized that this could be applied as a compiling method for ML.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Caml was designed and developed first by INRIA's Formel team headed by Gérard Huet.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] The first implementation of Caml was created in 1987 and was further developed until 1992.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Though it was spearheaded by Ascánder Suárez, Pierre Weis and Michel Mauny carried on with development after he left in 1988.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Guy Cousineau is quoted recalling that his experience with programming language implementation was initially very limited, and that there were multiple inadequacies for which he is responsible.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Between 1990 and 1991, Xavier Leroy designed a new implementation of Caml based on a bytecode interpreter written in C.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] In addition to this, Damien Doligez wrote a memory management system, also known as a sequential garbage collector, for this implementation.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] This new implementation, known as Caml Light, replaced the old Caml implementation and ran on small desktop machines.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] In the following years, libraries such as Michel Mauny's syntax manipulation tools appeared and helped promote the use of Caml in educational and research teams.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] In 1995, Xavier Leroy released Caml Special Light, which was an improved version of Caml.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] An optimizing native-code compiler was added to the bytecode compiler, which greatly increased performance to comparable levels with mainstream languages such as C++.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Also, Leroy designed a high-level module system inspired by the module system of Standard ML which provided powerful facilities for abstraction and parameterization and made larger-scale programs easier to build.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Didier Rémy and Jérôme Vouillon designed an expressive type system for objects and classes, which was integrated within Caml Special Light.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] This led to the emergence of the Objective Caml language, first released in 1996 and subsequently renamed to OCaml in 2011.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] This object system notably supported many prevalent object-oriented idioms in a statically type-safe way, while those same idioms caused unsoundness or required runtime checks in languages such as C++ or Java.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] In 2000, Jacques Garrigue extended Objective Caml with multiple new features such as polymorphic methods, variants, and labeled and optional arguments.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Language improvements have been incrementally added for the last two decades to support the growing commercial and academic codebases in OCaml.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] The OCaml 4.0 release in 2012 added Generalized Algebraic Data Types (GADTs) and first-class modules to increase the flexibility of the language.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] The OCaml 5.0.0 release in 2022 is a complete rewrite of the language runtime, removing the global GC lock and adding effect handlers via delimited continuations.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] These changes enable support for shared-memory parallelism and color-blind concurrency, respectively.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml's development continued within the Cristal team at INRIA until 2005, when it was succeeded by the Gallium team.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Subsequently, Gallium was succeeded by the Cambium team in 2019.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] As of 2023, there are 23 core developers of the compiler distribution from a variety of organizations and 41 developers for the broader OCaml tooling and packaging ecosystem.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] In 2023, the OCaml compiler was recognised with ACM SIGPLAN's Programming Languages Software Award.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml features a static type system, type inference, parametric polymorphism, tail recursion, pattern matching, first class lexical closures, functors (parametric modules), exception handling, effect handling, and incremental generational automatic garbage collection.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml is notable for extending ML-style type inference to an object system in a general-purpose language.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] This permits structural subtyping, where object types are compatible if their method signatures are compatible, regardless of their declared inheritance (an unusual feature in statically typed languages).
[src:reasonml/ocaml] A foreign function interface for linking to C primitives is provided, including language support for efficient numerical arrays in formats compatible with both C and Fortran.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml also supports creating libraries of OCaml functions that can be linked to a *main* program in C, so that an OCaml library can be distributed to C programmers who have no knowledge or installation of OCaml.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] Although OCaml does not have a macro system as an indivisible part of the language (metaprogramming), i.e. built-in support for preprocessing, the OCaml platform does officially support a library for writing such preprocessors.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] These can be of two types: one that works at the source code level (as in C), and one that works on the Abstract Syntax Tree level.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] The latter, which is called PPX, acronym for Pre-Processor eXtension, is the recommended one.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] The native code compiler is available for many platforms, including Unix, Microsoft Windows, and Apple macOS.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] The bytecode compiler supports operation on any 32- or 64-bit architecture when native code generation is not available, requiring only a C compiler.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml bytecode and native code programs can be written in a multithreaded style, with preemptive context switching.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] OCaml threads in the same domain execute by time sharing only.
[src:reasonml/ocaml] However, an OCaml program can contain several domains.
