[src:reasonml/pattern-matching] SNOBOL (*StriNg Oriented and symBOlic Language*) is a computer programming language developed between 1962 and 1967 at AT&T Bell Laboratories by David J.
[src:reasonml/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 stands apart from most programming languages by having patterns as a first-class data type (*i.e.* a data type whose values can be manipulated in all ways permitted to any other data type in the programming language) and by providing operators for pattern concatenation and alternation.
[src:reasonml/pattern-matching] Strings generated during execution can be treated as programs and executed.
[src:reasonml/pattern-matching] SNOBOL was quite widely taught in larger US universities in the late 1960s and early 1970s and was widely used in the 1970s and 1980s as a text manipulation language in the humanities.
[src:reasonml/pattern-matching] Since SNOBOL's creation, newer languages such as AWK and Perl have made string manipulation by means of regular expressions fashionable.
[src:reasonml/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 patterns, however, subsume Backus–Naur form (BNF) grammars, which are equivalent to context-free grammars and more powerful than regular expressions.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] Since Reason is an alternate syntax to OCaml, they share the same characteristics.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] Both languages are general-purpose, functional and object-oriented.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] While Reason compiles down to native code via OCaml's toolchain, it specifically differs in its syntax, error messaging, and editor tooling.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] This allows Reason to provide an experience more similar to JavaScript or TypeScript for developers.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] Reason’s syntax is more similar to JavaScript and other C-style languages than to OCaml.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] For example, Reason tends to use curly braces to delimit blocks and semicolons for separating statements, while OCaml primarily uses parentheses or `begin`/`end` keywords to delimit blocks, with nothing separating declarations.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] Reason also defines functions via an arrow-like syntax (rather than OCaml's `fun` keyword), and calling a function requires parentheses around its arguments.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] Other notable differences include naming the pattern matching keyword `switch` (instead of `match`), and reformatting error messages to be more familiar to JavaScript programmers.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] The Reason community officially provides ReasonReact as a solution for web applications based on the React framework.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] Jordan Walke, creator of the React web framework, first released Reason in 2016 while employed at Facebook.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] In the same year, Bloomberg L.P. introduced BuckleScript, a compiler which compiled OCaml to JavaScript.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] As both projects were influenced by JavaScript, Reason and BuckleScript soon became an integrated toolchain, allowing Reason to target JavaScript.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] However, the Reason team and the BuckleScript team had different priorities.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] The Reason team wanted to maintain compatibility with the OCaml ecosystem, while the BuckleScript team wanted to be able to change the syntax to give the best developer experience to JavaScript programmers.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] In 2020, BuckleScript introduced a new syntax that started to diverge from Reason.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] A month later, the BuckleScript team rebranded its toolchain to ReScript, to focus solely on the JavaScript ecosystem and essentially becoming its own language, distinct from Reason.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] To maintain the ability for Reason to target JavaScript, António Monteiro forked a version of BuckleScript before it was rebranded as ReScript, and changed it to bring it closer to the OCaml ecosystem.
[src:reasonml/reason-programming-language] The fork, named Melange, released its first stable version in 2023.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:reasonml/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
